 the world, whose uncontrolled effects are changing the planet itself. Advancing a new concept of the meme, called the ‘technical meme’, as the primary agent of cognitive extension and technical embodiment, the author proposes a theory of the ‘extended self’ encompassing material and spatial as well as psychological and social elements. Drawing upon research from philosophy, psychology and the neurosciences, the book presents a new approach to environmental and cultural studies that will appeal to a broad readership searching for insights into the crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitecture and society. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh  aBernard Stiegler.  aautopoiesis.  acognitive roots.  acombinativity.  aconcept of the self.  aextended self.  agroup identities.  ahuman body.  ahuman evolution.  ahuman perception.  aindividual identities.  amemes.  aneo-Darwinian concepts.  aorthodox evolutionary theory.  apersonal powers.  ascope of inquiry.  aspatial cognition.  atheory of extended minds.  avernacular architecture.1 aAbel, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez9783111283579oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526114297423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526114297/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPb2014